Steps to reproduce:

I have this piece of code :(ignore the missing ids)



<div class=leftnavi>
	<div class=navbutton id=userlist>Benutzerliste</div>
	<div class=navbutton id=></div>
	<div class=navbutton id=></div>
	<div class=navbutton id=></div>
	<div class=navbutton id=></div>
	<br>
	<div class=navbutton id=>Webseite</div>
	<br>
	<div class=navbutton id=>Ausloggen</div>
</div>


with this CSS:

.leftnavi {
  background: white none repeat scroll 0 0;
  border-bottom: 1px solid black;
  border-right: 1px solid black;
  display: inline;
  float: left;
  padding-top: 1em;
  padding-bottom: 1em;
  border-radius: 0 0 1em 0;
  padding-bottom: 1em;
}

and here comes the error : 

.leftnavi > DIV:nth-child(odd) {
	background: #eaeaea;
}


Actual results:

the "even" and "odd" DIV's are miscalculated.

The css rule clearly referes to an even or odd DIV, but instead all elements are counted, this includes the <br> elements. This leads to the situation, that the last two DIV get the same background color, which is not what was intended.




Expected results:

the <br> are not refered to, so they do not count for the even or odd calculation of those DIV's. The last and the second last DIV should end up with different background colors.
